{
  "text": "We began screening a wide range of ionic liquids to perform the Barbier-type In-mediated allylation. Thus, when allyl bromide and benzaldehyde were mixed with indium powder in [bmim] [BF4] (where bmim = 1-butyl-3-methylimidazolium), the corresponding homoallylic alcohol 1 was obtained in good yield and in a shorter time (5 h) than that previously reported [CITATION_1] (entry 1, Table 1 We next focused on the allylation involving a reductive transmetalation of a \u03c0-allylpalladium(II) with In(I), in which a variety of solvents can be used [CITATION_2] . Among the ionic liquids employed, as above [bmim] [BF4] gave the best yield (entry 1, Table 2 We next focused on the allylation involving a reductive transmetalation of a \u03c0-allylpalladium(II) with In(I), in which a variety of solvents can be used [CITATION_3] . Among the ionic liquids employed, as above [bmim] [BF 4 ] gave the best yield (entry 1, Table 2 including halides, are required in the crotylation of aldehydes depending on the nature of the ionic liquid employed.",
  "citation_candidates": [
